distribution, so I'm looking at a combined thermal floor that's still reasonable.\n\nWhen I add back the 1/f component at 10kHz, the total comes to roughly 101 nV/√Hz—just barely meeting the 100 nV/√Hz spec. I'm considering whether I need to push the optimization further by adjusting the W/L ratios on the cascode transistors to reduce their noise contribution.\n\nLet me recalculate with larger dimensions for M7/M8 at W=4µm L=8µm. This brings the 1/f noise down significantly, and at 10kHz I'm getting around 97 nV/√Hz, which comfortably clears the spec. So my approach is to scale up M7/M8 and M9/M10 to these larger dimensions and add a tail cascode to further improve performance.\n\nNow I need to add M11c for CMRR, fix the PSRR testbench with VDD-tracking bias, and re-tune all the bias voltages. The challenge is that going from W=0.36µm L=1µm to W=4µm L=8µm is a massive change—the operating point will shift dramatically. Let me work through the bias requirements for the new geometry, particularly for M7 where I need to ensure it stays in saturation with the right gate voltage.\n\nThe real constraint is that M9, M10, and M11 all share the same gate bias vbn and form a current mirror. Since I'm potentially changing M9's dimensions, I need to recalculate the current ratios based on the W/L values to ensure the tail current and cascode currents are properly matched. u L=4u (WL=32µm², 3.7× improvement), keeping L matched with M11 for the current mirror. For the cascode transistors M7/M8, I can vary L freely, so I'm bumping them to W=2u L=16u for a 89× improvement in area. This shifts the noise contributions—M7/M8 drops to 2.2× the input pair, while M9/M10 rises slightly to 2.6× due to the gm ratio changing with the wider width. But now I'm realizing that increasing M9's width so dramatically will lower its overdrive voltage and boost its transconductance, which affects the whole mirror behavior.\n\nLet me work through the math more carefully. As I increase the W/L ratio, the transconductance scales with the square root of that ratio, so gm grows proportionally to √(W/L). A larger gm from M9 actually increases its noise contribution to the input, even though the thermal noise per unit area decreases. I increase W from 2.15u to 8u (3.72×), gm increases by √3.72 = 1.93×.\n\nThe 1/f noise power spectral density of the drain current:\nSid_1f = Kf × gm² / (Cox² × WL × f)\n\nThe input-referred noise from M9:\nSn_M9_referred = Sid_1f_M9 / gm1² = Kf × gm9² / (Cox² × WL_M9 × f × gm1²)\n\nSo the contribution is proportional to gm9²/WL_M9. With the change:\n- gm9²: increases by (1.93)² = 3.72×\n- WL_M9: increases from 8.6µm² to 32µm² = 3.72×\n- Net: 3.72/3.72 = 1× — no change!\n\nInteresting — scaling W doesn't actually affect M9's input-referred noise because gm² and WL both scale proportionally with W. The noise contribution depends only on L, not W. So I'd need to increase L instead to reduce M9's noise, which would also require adjusting M11's L to maintain the current mirror ratio. For M7/M8, increasing L from 1u to 16u would decrease gm by 4× while reducing the noise contribution through the WL term. m7²: decreases by 16×\n- WL: increases by 16×\n- gm7²/WL: decreases by 16/16 = 1× — no change!\n\nWait, that can't be right. Let me redo this more carefully.\n\ngm = √(2µCox × (W/L) × Id)\ngm² = 2µCox × (W/L) × Id\n\nSid_1f = Kf_over_Cox2 / (W × L × f) × gm² = Kf_over_Cox2 × 2µCox × Id / (L² × f)\n\nSo Sid_1f ∝ 1/L²!\n\nInput-referred from M9: Sid_M9/gm1² ∝ 1/(L_M9² × gm1²)\n\nNow I'm seeing that the input-referred noise from M9 depends on gm1² = 2µCox × (W1/L1) × Id1, which means the contribution scales as L1/(L_M9² × W1 × Id1) — completely independent of M9's width. Increasing L_M9 from 4µ to 16µ cuts the 1/f noise by 16×, while pushing L_M7/M8 from 1µ to 16µ gives a 256× reduction. But there's a tradeoff: the drain current noise itself scales as 1/L², so doubling the channel length reduces that component by 4×.\n\nNow I'm working through the input-referred noise from M7 more carefully, deriving how the flicker noise formula combines with the transconductance squared in the denominator. Continuing with the input-referred noise from M1, then working out the ratio between the two contributions to see which dominates the total flicker noise at the input.\n\nWith the current dimensions where L1 is 14 micrometers and L7 is 1 micrometer, the noise ratio comes out to about 196 times higher from M7. I'm testing different channel lengths for M7 to find the sweet spot—if I stretch L7 to 8 micrometers the ratio drops to roughly 3 times, matching it to 14 micrometers eliminates the difference entirely, but going to 16 micrometers actually flips it and makes M7 contribute less noise than the input pair.\n\nThe pattern is clear: for flicker noise, the channel length is what matters, not the width, and the contribution scales with the square of the input-to-device length ratio. To keep noise down across the board, I should set all NMOS transistors to have channel lengths at least as long as the input pair's 14 micrometers. My approach is to bump M7 and M8 up from 1 micrometer to 14 micrometers, do the same for M9 and M10 from 4 micrometers to 14 micrometers, and then verify the overall noise performance.\n\nThe complication is that changing the channel length shifts the threshold voltage, which throws off the bias point. Since M9 and M10 form a current mirror with M11, I need to keep their dimensions matched for proper mirroring—so M11 also needs to go to 14 micrometers. With these longer channels, the aspect ratios become much smaller, which means I'll need to adjust the bias voltage to maintain the target 500 nanoamp current. The trade-offs are getting tangled, so I need to think through whether this approach is actually worth the added complexity.\n\nLooking at the broader picture, the PMOS fold transistors are already at 20 micrometers and the input pair at 14 micrometers, so extending the NMOS cascodes and current sources to similar long-channel lengths would be consistent with a low-noise design philosophy. I'm going to try a specific set of changes: making the fold cascode transistors much wider and longer to match the input pair, extending the mirror transistors to 14 micrometers for consistency, and adding a cascode device for improved common-mode rejection.\n\nOnce I make these changes, I'll need to re-tune the bias voltages since the threshold voltage will shift with the longer channel lengths. The mirror ratio should stay the same since both transistors scale proportionally, but I'll need to run a DC simulation to find the correct bias point rather than trying to hand-calculate everything. that's still not enough headroom. I need to combine strategies—increasing the tail current source's output impedance with a cascode stage will give me the multiplicative gain I need to push CMRR above 60 dB. So I'm going to lengthen the channel lengths across the input pair and current mirrors to reduce noise, add a cascode to the tail, and then retune all the bias voltages to hit the right operating points.\n\nModifying the OTA schematic now... Completing the cascode stage definitions and current source mirrors, but I'm noticing a potential issue—M7 and M8 are both controlled by the same bias voltage vbcn, which could create matching problems or unintended coupling between the two output branches. So even though M7 and M11c share the same gate bias, their source voltages differ because they're stacked on different transistors—M9 versus M11. Since M9 and M11 have similar specs but different currents (250nA vs 500nA), the source voltages will be slightly different, which means M7 and M11c will have different Vgs values, but as long as both stay in saturation, the circuit should work.\n\nNow I need to recalculate the bias voltages for the longer-channel devices. With L=14u, the threshold voltages will be higher, so I'll need to increase vbn and adjust vbcn accordingly. My plan is to update the OTA schematic first, then run a DC sweep to find the correct bias points. M7/M8 at L=14u will reduce the cascode transconductance since gm scales with √(W/L), and with W=2u that gives a ratio of only 0.143—I need to check if this impacts the gain significantly at that operating point. 250nA is:\ngm = √(2µCox×0.143×250n) \n\nFor NMOS µCox ≈ 100 µA/V² in SKY130:\ngm = √(2×100e-6×0.143×250e-9) = √(7.15e-12) = 2.67µA/V = 2.67µS\n\nPreviously M7/M8 at W=0.36u, L=1u: W/L = 0.36:\ngm = √(2×100e-6×0.36×250e-9) = √(1.8e-11) = 4.24µS\n\nSo gm decreases from 4.24µS to 2.67µS. The cascode effectiveness depends on gm × ro, which should still be very high. Even though lower gm means less impedance boosting, the much longer channel length gives a dramatically higher output resistance that more than compensates—gm×ro actually increases. The DC gain should be fine, and while the UGB might drop slightly from parasitics, it was already well above the 30kHz minimum at 34.4kHz. I'm ready to implement these changes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":694,"cache_read_input_tokens":86841,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":694},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dc3cf414-60b5-4244-9a30-3b9794da6520","uuid":"fee3b974-14ea-4fec-adaa-2749e184ba2c"}
