{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011zR9AVQvZ27xLxHQCPT4xC","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→* VibroSense Folded-Cascode OTA — SKY130A v8\n     2→* Low-noise design: long-L NMOS for reduced 1/f noise\n     3→* Cascoded tail for high CMRR\n     4→\n     5→.subckt ota_foldcasc vinp vinn vout vdd vss vbn vbcn vbp vbcp\n     6→\n     7→* Input Pair (W=5u L=14u for low 1/f noise)\n     8→XM1 fold_p vinp tail vss sky130_fd_pr__nfet_01v8 W=5u L=14u nf=1\n     9→XM2 fold_n vinn tail vss sky130_fd_pr__nfet_01v8 W=5u L=14u nf=1\n    10→\n    11→* Tail (500nA) — cascoded for high CMRR\n    12→* M11: long L for high ro. M11c: wide W for minimal Vdsat, gate=vbn\n    13→XM11  tail_int vbn vss vss sky130_fd_pr__nfet_01v8 W=3.8u L=14u nf=1\n    14→XM11c tail vbn tail_int vss sky130_fd_pr__nfet_01v8 W=20u L=1u nf=1\n    15→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dc3cf414-60b5-4244-9a30-3b9794da6520","uuid":"be3cf0f4-e6c4-479f-ac1a-17385633c9af","timestamp":"2026-03-23T11:07:36.474Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/ubuntu/analog-ai-chips/vibrosense/01_ota/ota_foldcasc.spice","content":"* VibroSense Folded-Cascode OTA — SKY130A v8\n* Low-noise design: long-L NMOS for reduced 1/f noise\n* Cascoded tail for high CMRR\n\n.subckt ota_foldcasc vinp vinn vout vdd vss vbn vbcn vbp vbcp\n\n* Input Pair (W=5u L=14u for low 1/f noise)\nXM1 fold_p vinp tail vss sky130_fd_pr__nfet_01v8 W=5u L=14u nf=1\nXM2 fold_n vinn tail vss sky130_fd_pr__nfet_01v8 W=5u L=14u nf=1\n\n* Tail (500nA) — cascoded for high CMRR\n* M11: long L for high ro. M11c: wide W for minimal Vdsat, gate=vbn\nXM11  tail_int vbn vss vss sky130_fd_pr__nfet_01v8 W=3.8u L=14u nf=1\nXM11c tail vbn tail_int vss sky130_fd_pr__nfet_01v8 W=20u L=1u nf=1\n","numLines":15,"startLine":1,"totalLines":75}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01HwYw7UJRQ3UVkL1Qq53sJa","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"For the noise, let me increase the input pair dimensions. Currently W=5u L=14u. The noise scales as 1/(W×L) for 1/f. If I double W to 10u: area = 140µm², noise decreases by √2.\n\nBut I also need to check: what's the dominant noise source? With M7/M8 at L=14u, their noise contribution ratio is (L_input/L_M7)² = (14/14)² = 1. So M7/M8 contribute the same as input pair.\n\nM9/M10 at L=14u: noise ratio = 1 as well.\n\n\nSo the three NMOS stages contribute equally to the total noise, giving me about 1.73× the base noise level. The measured 448 nV/rtHz at 1kHz means each equivalent source is around 259 nV/rtHz. To get below 200 nV/rtHz total, I need to reduce the base noise to about 115 nV/rtHz—roughly a 2.25× reduction.\n\nFor the 1/f noise, that means I need to increase the input pair's W/L ratio by about 5×. The current 70µm² would need to become 350µm², but going to something like W=10u L=35u would throw off the operating point too much. Let me try smaller adjustments: W=10u L=14u gives 140µm², reducing noise by 0.71× down to 318 nV/rtHz—still above target. W=20u L=14u gets me to 280µm², cutting the noise in half to 224 nV/rtHz, which is closer but still a bit high.\n\nPushing to W=20u L=20u (400µm²) means the other NMOS pairs at L=14u now contribute disproportionately more noise—the ratio between them becomes about 2.04 each. Working through the total noise contribution, I get around 244 nV/rtHz, which is still above the 200 target. The fundamental problem is that keeping M7/M8 and M9/M10 at the shorter L=14u length makes them noisier relative to the input pair.\n\nSo I need to match the channel lengths across all NMOS devices. Let me try setting everything to L=20u—the input pair stays at W=20u L=20u, while M7/M8 become W=2u L=20u and M9/M10 become W=2.15u L=20u. Now the noise ratios flatten to 1 for both cascode pairs, which should reduce the total contribution significantly.\n\nLooking back at the original design, the problem was clear: M1/M2 had L=14u while M7/M8 were only L=1u and M9/M10 were L=4u, creating huge noise ratios of 196 and 12.25 respectively. That added up to about 209× the base noise from the input pair. If the measured noise was 923 nV/√Hz, the base contribution from just M1/M2 was only around 63 nV/√Hz. By equalizing all the channel lengths, I'm eliminating those large ratio penalties.\n\nWith the new design where everything is L=20u, the ratios collapse to 1 for all stages, so the total noise becomes just √3 times the base noise of the input pair. The new base is lower too because of the larger WL product—scaling down to about 26.7 nV/√Hz. That gives me a total of roughly 46 nV/√Hz at 1kHz, which is well below the 200 nV/√Hz target. Even accounting for higher frequencies, this approach should work.\n\nNow I'm checking the 10kHz performance. The 1/f component drops to about 14.6 nV/√Hz, and I need to add the thermal noise contribution. With the new transistor dimensions and bias current, the transconductance works out to around 7 µS, which gives a thermal noise of about 39.5 nV/√Hz per NMOS source. With three NMOS stages contributing, that's roughly 68 nV/√Hz from thermal noise alone, and I'm combining that with the 1/f component to get the total at 10kHz.\n\nThe total noise floor comes out to about 70 nV/√Hz, which is well under the 100 nV/√Hz target—that's good. However, the W/L ratio of 1 with these dimensions gives an overdrive voltage of about 71 mV, which is slightly above the 50 mV minimum I'd prefer. Now I need to revisit the bias network for the cascode transistors and make sure the mirror matching is tight, especially since I'm using longer channel lengths.\n\nThe key issue is that M11 is at L=14u while M9/M10 are at L=20u, which throws off the current mirror ratio. I should make M11 also L=20u to keep them matched. With all the NMOS devices now at L=20u and the input pair at W=20u, I'll need to recalculate the bias voltages. For M7/M8, I need to size the width appropriately to maintain the ~250 nA current while keeping the overdrive voltage above 50 mV given the longer channel length.\n\nNow I'm working through the width calculation for the cascode transistors — with W=2u and L=20u, the overdrive voltage comes out too high at 224 mV, which eats up too much headroom. I'm trying W=4u instead to get a more reasonable overdrive voltage for the cascode stage.\n\nWith the updated dimensions, the cascode overdrive drops to 158 mV, leaving plenty of margin since M7's drain-source voltage is well above the saturation requirement. For M9 and M10, I'm calculating a similar overdrive around 216 mV, but the current design only has 184 mV of headroom, which is getting tight.\n\nI'm widening M9 and M10 to bring the overdrive down to 158 mV, though even at 184 mV it's borderline. Rather than chase the exact numbers, I'll set these dimensions and run a simulation to see how the bias point actually settles. For M11, I need to determine the width while keeping the length at 20 micrometers, with the current controlled by the bias voltage. M9/M10 for good mirror.\n\nLet me try:\n- M1/M2: W=20u L=20u\n- M7/M8: W=4u L=20u\n- M9/M10: W=4u L=20u (wider for lower Vov and more Vds headroom)\n- M11: W=7.5u L=20u (to get W/L ratio for ~500nA mirror: W_M11/L_M11 ≈ 2×(W_M9/L_M9) since M11 carries 2× current)\n  Actually: M9 carries ~250nA, M11 carries ~500nA. Mirror ratio: (W11/L11)/(W9/L9) = 500/250 = 2. So W11 = 2×W9 = 8u.\n- M11c: W=20u L=1u (cascode, wide for low Vdsat)\n\nWith these dimensions, the bias voltage vbn will need adjustment since M1/M2 have different characteristics. I'm also reconsidering vbcn—at 0.88V it might not work well with the longer channel lengths on M7/M8. Rather than tweaking endlessly, I should just implement these changes and sweep the bias voltages to find what works. The real priority here is tackling the noise issue. I've already seen improvement by extending the channel lengths on M7/M8 and M9/M10 to L=14u, which dropped the noise from 923 to 448 nV/rtHz. Let me push this further and try L=30u on those devices to see if I can get even better noise performance. I need to increase the input pair's width to reduce its noise contribution. Bumping W to 15u gives WL=210µm², which cuts the noise per source down to 150 nV/rtHz, bringing the total to 180 nV/rtHz—that meets the spec. At 10kHz the 1/f noise drops to 57 nV/rtHz, and with the larger width the transconductance increases, which helps with the thermal noise floor.\n\nComputing the thermal contribution with W=15u gives about 38.8 nV/rtHz per source, totaling 67.2 nV/rtHz across both. Combined with the 1/f component, I'm getting 88 nV/rtHz at 10kHz, which passes. So my device sizing is locked in: M1/M2 at 15u/14u, M7/M8 at 2u/30u, and M9/M10 at 2.15u/30u.\n\nBut now I'm realizing the mirror mismatch—if M9/M10 are at L=30u, then M11 needs to match at L=30u too, which means I need to retune the bias voltage. Looking at the overdrive voltage for M9/M10 with these dimensions, I'm getting 0.264V, but the source voltage is only sitting at 0.184V—that's not enough headroom. I need to widen M9/M10 further to bring down the overdrive voltage and fix this saturation issue.\n\nWith W=8u and L=30u, the overdrive voltage drops to 0.137V, which gives me the headroom I need. The 1/f noise ratio stays the same since it only depends on channel length, not width. So my final design is M1/M2 at 15u/14u for lower noise, M7/M8 at 4u/30u for low noise with long channels, and M9/M10 at 8u/30u to satisfy both the saturation constraint and noise requirements.\n\nNow I'm checking whether M11 at 16u/30u can deliver the 500nA bias current while maintaining the same overdrive voltage and verifying the threshold voltage at this channel length.\n\nFor the current mirror, M9 should pull exactly half the current of M11 since the width ratio is 2:1 with matched lengths, which checks out perfectly. Now I'm working through M7/M8 with their smaller 4u width to see what overdrive voltage they need...\n\nThe overdrive voltage comes out to about 0.194V, so with threshold voltage factored in, the gate bias needs to be around 0.88V. That's still within the range I calculated for vbcn. Let me verify M7 has enough headroom in saturation before finalizing these bias points. Now I'm calculating the tail voltage by working through the cascode stack—the tail node sits around 0.2V above the bottom, and the input pair source voltage depends on M1's gate-source drop. With M1 sized at 15u by 14u, I'm finding its overdrive voltage comes to about 68mV, giving a gate-source voltage near 0.657V, which means the tail voltage lands around 0.24V.\n\nThe cascode device M11c needs to stay in saturation with only about 43mV of headroom, and since it's a wide device at 20u by 1u, it can easily handle the required current with a saturation voltage well below that. Everything checks out, so I'm ready to simulate and dial in the exact bias voltage.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":511,"cache_read_input_tokens":122012,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":511},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dc3cf414-60b5-4244-9a30-3b9794da6520","uuid":"2ce968b0-629f-4c7e-a53f-2d0bf3abab09"}
