{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01EQDUR45te97wMrYu2AQ5vU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Problems:\n1. Tail current never reaches 500nA even at vbn=0.60 (only 291nA). The L=50u devices need much more Vgs.\n2. M1 Vov is very low (45mV at vbn=0.60, below 50mV minimum).\n\nThe Vov_M1 issue: with L=20u for M1, at 250nA, Vov is about 36-45mV. Need > 50mV. This means L=20u is too long for W=5u with 250nA — the device operates near the threshold.\n\n\nThe tail current problem is fundamental—M11 at L=50u simply can't deliver 500nA at practical bias voltages. I'm running into a wall with this current level. Let me step back and reconsider the whole approach. The real issue is that 500nA forces me to use very long channels for low noise, but those long devices can't actually carry the current I need in strong inversion. If I bump the tail current up to 1µA instead, I get better gm scaling and the noise floor drops significantly without needing such extreme device dimensions.\n\nNow I'm checking what happens with this higher current. With each input transistor pulling 500nA from a 1µA tail, I can use smaller devices and still maintain reasonable overdrive voltages. Let me verify the math: at W=5u and L=14u with 500nA, the overdrive voltage should scale with the square root of current, so it jumps from 57mV to about 81mV. That's still workable, and the smaller geometry is much more practical than what I was trying before.\n\nThe tail voltage stays around 0.23V, which is fine. More importantly, the transconductance nearly doubles to about 6.8µS per device, which significantly improves the noise performance. The thermal noise drops from 47nV to 33nV per root-Hz, and the 1/f noise actually halves since it scales inversely with gm² in strong inversion.\n\nBut scaling up the current to 500nA means I'd need to adjust the W/L ratios for all the other devices too, which gets messy. Let me try something simpler instead—what if I just parallelize the input pair? I could use four identical instances of the differential pair, each with W=5u and L=14u, all sharing the same tail node.\n\nThat would give each instance only 62.5nA of current, but then the overdrive voltage drops to about 28.5mV, which fails the 50mV minimum check. So maybe I need to increase the tail current to 1µA instead and recalculate from there. 4 instances carries 125nA:\nVov = 57 × √(125/250) = 57 × 0.707 = 40.3mV. Still below 50mV.\n\nWhat about 2 parallel instances with 1µA tail? Each carries 250nA with W=5u L=14u: Vov = 57mV ✓. But total WL = 2×70 = 140µm².\n\nWith 1µA tail, the noise per device is:\n1/f: same WL=70µm² per instance, 2 in parallel → effective WL=140µm². And gm = 4.8µS per instance (same current per instance).\n\nFor N parallel input pairs, the total transconductance scales linearly while uncorrelated noise sources combine as √N, so the input-referred noise actually improves by a factor of √N. With 2 parallel pairs I get a 1.41× improvement, and with 4 pairs it's 2×. Let me work through what this means for the 4-pair configuration.\n\nWith 4 parallel instances per side at 125nA each, the total tail current would be 2µA, but adding the fold current pushes me over the 2µA budget. Dropping to 2 instances with 1µA tail keeps me right at the limit while maintaining the same current per device and acceptable overdrive voltage. The effective input-referred noise becomes 224 nV/√Hz at 1kHz, and the total transconductance reaches 9.6µS per side. I need to trace through the current distribution more carefully in the folded-cascode topology—the supply current flows through the PMOS fold transistors from VDD, then down through the cascodes and current sources to ground, so I should account for both the fold current and the tail current properly to see if I can fit within the 2µA budget. I'm working through the current budget with concrete numbers—at 500nA tail current, I'm hitting about 1µA total, and if I bump the tail current to 1µA, I can stay under 2µA with modest fold currents around 600nA per side. Let me explore what happens if I push the tail current even higher to 1.5µA. I need to recalculate the total supply current more carefully. The key insight is that Idd equals the sum of currents through the PMOS load transistors, which breaks down as Itail plus twice the cascode current. Let me work through what the actual current draw would be with my proposed values. Now I'm checking how the input-referred 1/f noise scales with the increased transconductance—doubling the current from 250nA to 500nA improves the noise figure by roughly 30%, bringing it down from 448 to 316 nV/√Hz.\n\nThat's still not quite enough, so I'm exploring whether I can use parallel instances to further reduce noise. With two parallel devices at 500nA each, the total tail current would be 2µA, but adding the cascode current pushes the total power consumption over the 2µA budget—even with minimal cascode current around 50nA, I'm already at 2.1µA. The power constraint is extremely tight, leaving almost no headroom for the folded-cascode topology, and I need to figure out the minimum fold current required while staying within budget.\n\nIf I reduce the tail current to 1.8µA and keep the cascode current minimal at around 20nA per device, I can stay just under the 2µA limit. At this operating point, each input device would have an overdrive voltage of about 108mV, giving me a transconductance of roughly 9.1µS per device. The noise would improve by a factor of 3.59 from the higher transconductance, bringing the spectral density down to around 236 nV/√Hz—still a bit above my 200 nV/√Hz target, but getting closer.\n\nThe real issue is that with such low currents in the NMOS current sources, they might not even be in saturation, which would degrade performance further. Given the tight power budget and the fundamental 1/f noise floor of the NMOS input pair at these dimensions and currents, I'm hitting a wall with this topology. I should explore switching to a PMOS input pair instead, since many processes show significantly lower 1/f noise in PMOS devices—potentially 10× better or more. to a PMOS input pair:\n- The 1/f noise from the input pair would be 3-10× lower\n- The folded-cascode topology works the same but mirrored\n\nBut changing to PMOS input pair is a major redesign. Let me consider...\n\nActually, the current design already has PMOS fold transistors with L=20u and total WL=168µm² per side. The PMOS 1/f noise is already low. The issue is the NMOS input pair.\n\nIf I swap to PMOS input pair and NMOS fold:\n- Input pair: PMOS W=5u L=14u\n- Fold: NMOS with long L\n- This fundamentally reduces the input-referred 1/f noise\n\nBut this requires a complete redesign of the OTA. The bias voltages, the connectivity, everything changes.\n\nLet me think through the topology more carefully. With a PMOS input pair, the sources connect to VDD through a tail current source, the drains feed into NMOS fold transistors at the fold nodes, and then PMOS cascode devices sit above those fold nodes connecting back to VDD. The output comes from the PMOS cascode side. This is essentially a mirror image of the standard folded-cascode, which means a complete restructuring of the circuit.\n\nGiven the noise reduction I'm seeing—from 923 nV/rtHz down to 448 nV/rtHz just by increasing the input pair length—I should verify whether the theoretical noise model is actually matching reality. The math suggests a 4× reduction was possible, but I only got 2×. That gap might tell me where the remaining noise is coming from and whether a topology swap is even necessary.\n\nRather than trying to perfect the hand calculations for BSIM4 flicker noise, which depends heavily on the specific PDK parameters, I think the faster path forward is to just run simulations with different designs and measure what actually happens.\n\nI'm looking at the key constraints I need to satisfy: tail current around 500nA, overdrive voltages above 50mV for the NMOS paths and 150mV for PMOS, everything in saturation, under 2µA total, noise below 200nV/√Hz at 1kHz, gain above 60dB, and unity-gain bandwidth between 30-150kHz.\n\nNow I'm wondering if switching to a PMOS input pair might help—the existing PMOS devices already have good length and overdrive voltage, so let me explore what happens if I use those for the input stage instead.\n\nThe tradeoff is clear: PMOS would give me much lower 1/f noise, but I'd lose the mobility advantage and need more area or current to maintain the same transconductance. That's a significant redesign, so let me first check if the current NMOS input pair can actually meet the noise spec with better optimization.\n\nLooking at my current numbers with the longer channel lengths, the input pair is now the dominant noise source. If I increase the width while keeping the overdrive voltage above 50mV, I can reduce the noise contribution—trying W=5µm with L=14µm gives me 70 in WL ratio and 57mV overdrive, or pushing to L=16µm should give me slightly better overdrive voltage.\n\nActually, let me try something more aggressive: I'll use three parallel instances of the input pair, each with W=5µm L=14µm, and increase the tail current to 1.5µA so each transistor only carries 250nA and maintains that 57mV overdrive. This gives me a total input pair area of 210µm², and I can adjust the fold current and cascode current to stay within my 2µA total supply budget.\n\nWith a fold current of 900nA per side, the cascode current works out to 150nA, keeping the total current at 1.8µA. For noise, the larger input pair area reduces the noise contribution by a factor of √3 compared to a single pair, which more than compensates for the area increase. So the 1/f noise actually doesn't scale with current in the SPICE2 model—it only depends on the device dimensions and frequency. That means three parallel devices each contribute the same noise voltage, which combines to give a √3 reduction when referred to the input, effectively equivalent to a single device with triple the channel width.\n\nLooking at the actual numbers, even with three parallel instances I'm getting 259 nV/√Hz at 1kHz, which overshoots my 200 nV/√Hz target. I need to calculate the required area: solving for WL gives me over 351 µm², which means I need five parallel instances instead—each with W=5µm and L=14µm—to keep the input pair noise below my budget.\n\nBut here's the problem: five parallel instances at 250nA each would push the tail current to 2.5µA, way over the 500±50nA specification. The spec is fixed, so I can't increase the tail current. If I try to distribute the 500nA across five instances, each transistor only gets 50nA, which gives me an overdrive voltage of about 25.5mV—below the 50mV minimum I need. I'm hitting a wall where the noise requirement and the current constraint are incompatible.\n\nLet me try a different angle: maybe I can use fewer parallel instances with longer channel lengths. With just two instances at 125nA each and a longer L, I might be able to hit the Vov target while keeping the tail current within spec. Or I could explore whether SKY130 has alternative transistor types—there might be low-threshold or low-noise variants that could help me meet the flicker noise spec without needing as much current.\n\nActually, looking at what's available in the minimal library, it seems like I'm limited to the standard 1.8V devices. But switching to PMOS for the input pair is worth considering since PMOS typically has an order of magnitude lower 1/f noise than NMOS in most processes.\n\nIf I can get the input pair noise down to around 82 nV/√Hz with PMOS, and account for the noise from the rest of the circuit, I'd be looking at total noise in the 100-150 nV/√Hz range, which is actually achievable. The challenge is that redesigning the OTA with a PMOS input pair would be substantial work, so I need to figure out what the minimum structural changes would be to make this work.\n\nThe key insight is switching to a PMOS-input folded-cascode topology where the input pair sources to VDD through a PMOS tail current source, then using NMOS fold transistors instead of PMOS ones, with NMOS cascode at the bottom and PMOS cascode at the top feeding the output.\n\nSketching out the circuit topology...\n\nActually, this is getting unwieldy to visualize mentally—let me just go with a straightforward PMOS-input folded cascode and flip all the polarities systematically. But wait, I should double-check those noise measurements at 1kHz with the specific transistor sizing before committing to a design.\n\nNow I'm working through the noise contribution from the PMOS fold transistors. With 20 instances per side and a combined transconductance around 4.34µS versus the input stage's 4.8µS, the referred noise scales by about 0.817. The effective gate area for the fold transistors comes out to roughly 168µm², and accounting for the typical 10:1 ratio between PMOS and NMOS flicker noise coefficients, I can estimate what the fold stage contributes to the overall input-referred noise floor.\n\nNormalizing against the input pair's noise at 70µm², the PMOS fold contribution works out to only about 3.4% of the input pair noise—essentially negligible. This confirms that the dominant noise sources are elsewhere in the circuit.\n\nRather than continuing to chase analytical optimization, I'm going to take a more practical approach and just run a few candidate designs through simulation to see which performs best. I've got the original design from v7 that gave 923 nV, v8 with longer channel lengths that dropped it to 448 nV, and now I want to test v10 with even more aggressive sizing to see if I can push the noise lower.\n\nThe tail current biasing is the real constraint here—with M11 at L=50u, the device becomes very weak and I need to push vbn higher to get adequate current. Let me sweep vbn up to 0.80 and see what tail current I can actually achieve.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":918,"cache_read_input_tokens":144098,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":918},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dc3cf414-60b5-4244-9a30-3b9794da6520","uuid":"a0c7ab06-7022-4ae8-ba21-73d41834489d"}
