{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01HmVoDRSLghhdrsQHNA7SK9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting. The CM gain:\n- 0.1Hz: 9.5 dB\n- 1Hz: 14.5 dB (this is what the verifier uses for cmrr_dc)\n- 10Hz: 13.2 dB\n- 100Hz: -1.5 dB\n- 1kHz: -21.4 dB\n\nThe CM gain peaks at low frequencies (around 1-10 Hz) and rolls off at higher frequencies. At 100Hz it's already near 0dB (1 V/V).\n\nThis pattern looks like the CM gain has a low-frequency behavior that peaks because of the interaction between the Lbreak inductor and the circuit.\n\n\nAt very low frequencies like 0.1Hz, the Lbreak inductor has enormous impedance while the AC coupling capacitor becomes nearly a short circuit, so the common-mode signal couples through the capacitor to the input. But there's also feedback through the inductor creating a loop that affects the differential signal, which explains why the gain peaks in this frequency range rather than monotonically increasing. e-10 V feedback creates a negligible differential signal at the output, so the 14.5 dB common-mode gain must be coming from somewhere else. Let me reconsider what happens when both inputs rise by 1V at low frequency—the tail current source impedance is so high that the tail current remains essentially constant, meaning M1 and M2 each carry half the tail current regardless of input voltage changes. The question is whether the fold node voltages actually shift when both inputs move together.\n\nWhen the common-mode input increases, the tail voltage follows it up by roughly the same amount to keep the gate-source voltage constant, but the fold node impedance is set by the PMOS load and NMOS cascode stack, which is relatively low. This means the fold voltage barely moves, so the input pair's drain-source voltage effectively decreases by the input change, which through channel-length modulation causes the drain current to change proportionally to the output impedance at that node.\n\nNow I'm realizing that both input transistors experience the same Vds change since they're in parallel at the tail, so they should have equal drain current changes — but the two fold nodes might have different output impedances depending on what's connected downstream. The fold_n side connects through a different path to the output than the fold_p side, which could create an asymmetry even in a symmetric circuit.\n\nAt 1Hz, the capacitive load at vout has extremely high impedance (around 16GΩ), so it's not really limiting the voltage swing there — the asymmetry must come from something else in the circuit topology.\n\nLet me reconsider the testbench setup itself. I just noticed that in the CMRR measurement, vinp connects directly to vcm while vinn connects to vcm through Cac and also has Lbreak feeding back from vout. At DC, that inductor shorts, putting the OTA into unity-gain feedback. For the AC common-mode test, both inputs nominally see the same 1V signal, but I need to trace through more carefully what's actually happening at vinn given the Cac coupling and the feedback path. Now I'm working through the voltage divider at the inverting input, accounting for the feedback path through the inductor. The differential input voltage ends up being proportional to the output with a tiny coupling factor, which creates a feedback term that slightly reduces the overall gain. Solving for the output voltage, I get a closed-loop expression where the gain is divided by a factor that depends on the differential gain and this coupling coefficient.\n\nWith realistic component values, this correction factor is negligible, so the measurement should be accurate. But I'm still puzzled about where the common-mode gain is coming from. Let me trace through what happens when both inputs rise together—the tail node also rises, which changes the voltage across the cascode transistor and could alter the tail current. The cascode is supposed to isolate the tail from these variations, but maybe there's a subtle effect I'm missing.\n\nActually, thinking about it more carefully: the cascode does provide significant isolation—the gain from tail voltage changes to the input pair's source is reduced by the cascode's gain factor of around 256. So any current variation in the tail should be tiny. There could be capacitive coupling through the cascode when the tail moves, but at 1 Hz those effects are negligible too.\n\nI'm going in circles trying to trace the CMRR analytically. Let me just run a different simulation setup and see if I can measure the common-mode gain directly.\n\nSetting up a testbench...\n\nI'm realizing that without feedback, the DC operating point becomes unstable—the output could drift to a rail or fail to converge entirely. Instead, I should run two separate AC analyses: one with a signal on the differential input to measure differential gain, and another with a common-mode signal to extract the common-mode gain, then calculate CMRR from those results.\n\nFor the differential case, I can use the existing testbench with the Lbreak feedback technique. For common-mode, I need to apply the same AC signal to both inputs while maintaining DC bias through feedback. But I'm running into a practical issue: I can't directly connect both a feedback resistor and a voltage source to the same node without creating conflicts. Let me reconsider the feedback topology to properly isolate the common-mode response.\n\nSetting up a testbench with both inputs at the same DC bias and AC magnitude...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":23274,"cache_read_input_tokens":159105,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":23274},"output_tokens":46,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dc3cf414-60b5-4244-9a30-3b9794da6520","uuid":"96bde0f2-d364-4110-a604-714dc4bad785"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01HmVoDRSLghhdrsQHNA7SK9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Rst9YwVCAgBihVE6X7gCY2","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cat > /tmp/tb_cmrr_v2.spice << 'EOF'\n* CMRR test: both inputs directly tied to same AC source\n.lib \"sky130_minimal.lib.spice\" tt\n.include \"ota_foldcasc.spice\"\nVdd vdd 0 dc 1.8\nVbn vbn 0 dc 0.634\nVbcn vbcn 0 dc 0.88\nVbp vbp 0 dc 0.73\nVbcp vbcp 0 dc 0.475\n\n* Both inputs tied together with same AC\nVcm_p vinp 0 dc 0.9 ac 1\nVcm_n vinn 0 dc 0.9 ac 1\n\nXota vinp vinn vout vdd 0 vbn vbcn vbp vbcp ota_foldcasc\nCL vout 0 10p\n\n.nodeset v(vout)=0.9\n\n.ac dec 100 0.1 1G\n\n.control\nrun\nmeas ac acm_dc FIND vdb(vout) AT=1\nmeas ac acm_10 FIND vdb(vout) AT=10\nmeas ac acm_100 FIND vdb(vout) AT=100\necho \"acm_dc = $&acm_dc\"\necho \"acm_10Hz = $&acm_10\"\necho \"acm_100Hz = $&acm_100\"\nquit\n.endc\n.end\nEOF\n/usr/bin/ngspice -b /tmp/tb_cmrr_v2.spice 2>&1 | grep \"acm\"","description":"CMRR test with direct-tied inputs","timeout":120000},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":23274,"cache_read_input_tokens":159105,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":23274},"output_tokens":46,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dc3cf414-60b5-4244-9a30-3b9794da6520","uuid":"bc5d65be-dc08-490f-aafa-4dc7b0f37f2d"}
