{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01AoaKDx6awuGuZXBBUSN21P","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still ~39 dB gain across all corners. The bypass caps didn't help. The gain is consistently ~39 dB which is much lower than the 66.8 dB from the AC testbench. The bias circuit is definitely interfering.\n\nWait, even the TT corner shows 39.3 dB, while tb_ota_ac.spice (also TT) gives 66.8 dB. The difference is the bias generation. The self-bias circuit must be creating a parallel signal path that loads the output.\n\nLet me look at the bias circuit more carefully. The vbp bias:\n\n\nThe bias PMOS is configured as a diode-connected transistor with its gate and drain tied together at vbp, and it's sourced from vdd—which means it's essentially functioning as another fold transistor just like M3 and M4 in the OTA. At AC frequencies, this creates an additional current path from vdd that's loading down the output node.\n\nNow I'm realizing that with the 1F bypass capacitor across vbp, the bias node becomes AC ground, so the gate-source voltage of the bias transistor stays constant at AC. This means the fold transistors (which also have their gates tied to vbp) see a fixed Vgs during AC operation, so they contribute only their output conductance to the vbp node—but since vbp is already bypassed to ground, this parasitic conductance doesn't significantly affect the circuit behavior.\n\nLet me trace through the vbcn bias network instead, which appears to be a cascode configuration where the drain of the first transistor feeds back to its own gate.\n\nAt AC, both vbcn and vbn are grounded through bypass capacitors, so the bias transistors are completely decoupled from the signal path. The current sources themselves act as ideal impedances at AC and shouldn't introduce gain loss.\n\nI should check whether the corner testbench is actually using the same AC analysis setup as my main testbench, or if there's a di